## Set up Framer Motion v11 in Next.js App Router

### 1. Install the package
- Run: `npm install framer-motion`
- Framer Motion v11 requires React 18+ and is ESM-only. It is compatible with Next.js 14+.
- No additional types package needed — types are bundled.

### 2. Understand the App Router constraint
- `motion` components use `useAnimation`, `useMotionValue`, and browser APIs — they are Client Components.
- Any component that imports from `framer-motion` and renders a `<motion.*>` element MUST have `'use client'` at the top.
- Server Components can render wrapper layout components that contain animated Client Components.

### 3. Basic motion component
- Create `src/components/animated-card.tsx`:
```tsx
'use client';

import { motion } from 'framer-motion';

export function AnimatedCard({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <motion.div
      initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }}
      animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
      transition={{ duration: 0.4, ease: 'easeOut' }}
      className="rounded-lg border p-4"
    >
      {children}
    </motion.div>
  );
}
```
- `initial` — state before animation starts.
- `animate` — state to animate to on mount.
- `exit` — state when element is removed (requires `AnimatePresence`).
- `transition` — timing and easing configuration.

### 4. Use variants for complex animations
- Variants let you define named states and orchestrate animations across parent/children:
```tsx
'use client';

import { motion } from 'framer-motion';

const containerVariants = {
  hidden: { opacity: 0 },
  visible: {
    opacity: 1,
    transition: {
      staggerChildren: 0.1, // animate children 100ms apart
    },
  },
};

const itemVariants = {
  hidden: { opacity: 0, x: -20 },
  visible: { opacity: 1, x: 0 },
};

export function AnimatedList({ items }: { items: string[] }) {
  return (
    <motion.ul variants={containerVariants} initial="hidden" animate="visible">
      {items.map((item) => (
        <motion.li key={item} variants={itemVariants}>
          {item}
        </motion.li>
      ))}
    </motion.ul>
  );
}
```
- Children automatically inherit `initial` and `animate` from the parent when using variants.

### 5. Add AnimatePresence for exit animations
- `AnimatePresence` enables the `exit` prop — without it, exit animations are skipped:
```tsx
'use client';

import { AnimatePresence, motion } from 'framer-motion';
import { useState } from 'react';

export function ToggleBox() {
  const [isVisible, setIsVisible] = useState(true);

  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setIsVisible((v) => !v)}>Toggle</button>
      <AnimatePresence>
        {isVisible && (
          <motion.div
            key="box"
            initial={{ opacity: 0, scale: 0.8 }}
            animate={{ opacity: 1, scale: 1 }}
            exit={{ opacity: 0, scale: 0.8 }}
            transition={{ duration: 0.2 }}
          >
            I animate in and out!
          </motion.div>
        )}
      </AnimatePresence>
    </>
  );
}
```
- IMPORTANT: Each child of `AnimatePresence` must have a unique stable `key` prop. Without it, React cannot track which element is entering or exiting.

### 6. Page transitions in App Router
- Create a reusable page wrapper `src/components/page-transition.tsx`:
```tsx
'use client';

import { motion } from 'framer-motion';

export function PageTransition({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <motion.main
      initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 10 }}
      animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
      transition={{ duration: 0.3 }}
    >
      {children}
    </motion.main>
  );
}
```
- Wrap page content in `src/app/(pages)/layout.tsx` or individual `page.tsx` files:
```tsx
// src/app/about/page.tsx
import { PageTransition } from '@/components/page-transition';

export default function AboutPage() {
  return (
    <PageTransition>
      <h1>About</h1>
    </PageTransition>
  );
}
```
- IMPORTANT: In Next.js App Router, full cross-route exit animations are not supported without workarounds because Next.js unmounts the old page before exit animations can play. Use enter-only transitions or a third-party router like `next-view-transitions` for true page transitions.

### 7. Scroll-triggered animations with useInView
- Animate elements as they scroll into the viewport:
```tsx
'use client';

import { motion, useInView } from 'framer-motion';
import { useRef } from 'react';

export function ScrollReveal({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const ref = useRef(null);
  const isInView = useInView(ref, { once: true, margin: '-100px' });

  return (
    <motion.div
      ref={ref}
      initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 40 }}
      animate={isInView ? { opacity: 1, y: 0 } : {}}
      transition={{ duration: 0.5, ease: 'easeOut' }}
    >
      {children}
    </motion.div>
  );
}
```
- `once: true` — animation only plays once (does not re-trigger on scroll back).
- `margin: '-100px'` — triggers 100px before the element enters the viewport.

### 8. Gesture interactions (hover, tap)
```tsx
'use client';

import { motion } from 'framer-motion';

export function InteractiveButton({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <motion.button
      whileHover={{ scale: 1.05 }}
      whileTap={{ scale: 0.95 }}
      transition={{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 400, damping: 17 }}
      className="rounded-md bg-blue-500 px-4 py-2 text-white"
    >
      {children}
    </motion.button>
  );
}
```

### 9. Verify the setup
- Run `npm run dev` and navigate to a page with animated components.
- Confirm animations play on mount, exit animations work when toggling elements, and scroll animations trigger correctly.
- Check the browser console for errors — missing `'use client'` or `key` props are the most common issues.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Error: Functions cannot be passed directly to Client Components`** — You imported `motion` in a Server Component without `'use client'`. Add `'use client'` to the top of the file.
- **Exit animations don't play** — Missing `<AnimatePresence>` wrapper around the conditionally rendered element.
- **Exit animations play for wrong element** — Missing or duplicate `key` prop on `AnimatePresence` children. Each child needs a unique stable key.
- **`useInView` always returns `false`** — You forgot to attach the `ref` to the DOM element: `<motion.div ref={ref} ...>`.
- **Animations re-trigger on every render** — Variants or transition objects are defined inside the component body and recreated on every render. Move them outside the component.
- **Layout shifts during animation** — Avoid animating `width`/`height` directly; use `scaleX`/`scaleY` or `layout` prop for smoother layout animations.
- **`Cannot find module 'framer-motion'`** — Package not installed. Run `npm install framer-motion`.
- **Hydration mismatch** — Using `motion` in a Server Component without `'use client'`. SSR renders static HTML; client hydrates with animated version, causing mismatch. Always use `'use client'`.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT import `motion` in Server Components without `'use client'` — it causes a hydration error.
- Do NOT define variant objects or transition objects inside the component function — they are recreated on every render and can cause unnecessary re-animations or infinite loops.
- Do NOT use Framer Motion for every micro-interaction — reserve it for meaningful transitions. Excessive animation degrades performance and UX.
- Do NOT forget `key` on `AnimatePresence` children — without it, exit animations are skipped silently.
- Do NOT animate CSS properties that trigger layout (e.g., `width`, `margin`, `padding`) directly — use the `layout` prop or transform-based properties (`x`, `y`, `scale`) for GPU-accelerated 60fps animations.
- Do NOT expect full route-level exit animations in Next.js App Router without additional tools — App Router unmounts outgoing pages synchronously.
